@NODE PPW "ProPassWord Documentation"

                             @{U}USING PROPASSWORD@{UU}

This is the one program of the two which doesn't need a helluva lot
explaining. But first, I shall tell you about the few CLI parameters that
there are (there are only a few, don't worry!)

Firstly, to get a list of commands, run ProPassWord from the CLI with ? as
a parameter, i.e.

   ProPassword ?

And the list of commands will be displayed. Here they are, explained a
little ;)

NOAUDIO = If your system crashes when you use ProPassWord, try setting this
          option. This disables audio feedback in the program, and can 
          sometimes help if your system crashes.

FORCE   = This parameter literally forces the program to run, even if the
          program is complaining about the system not being good enough to
          handle ProPassWord. This means that if you are on a 68000
          equipped machine, you can still use PPW. You should expect
          crashes though!

And those are the only parameters I need explain! Now on to the main
program itself..

Put simply, all you do with this program is enter your username
and password, and assuming that you enter them correctly, you will be
granted access. 

If you do not get them correct, the program flashes different colours, the
Power LED on your Amiga flashes, and then you are returned to the dialog
box, ready to enter a different password.

When you get the password correct, the program appends the details to the
log file and exits.

And that's it! All there is to it!

                        @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GPPW "ProPassWord Documentation"

                         @{U}USING GENERATEPROPASSWORD@{UU}

GenerateProPassWord (known as GPPW from here on) generates the necessary 
password lists for use with ProPassWord itself. Note that the program is CLI
only, so obviously, you'll have to run it from the CLI!

Once you have started the program, the program information will appear,
followed by a menu consisting of the following options:

   @{" " LINK GPPW-LOADPWL} - 1) Load in a PassWord list
   @{" " LINK GPPW-SAVEPWL} - 2) Save a PassWord list
   @{" " LINK GPPW-CNFPW} - 3) Config PassWord (NEW)
   @{" " LINK GPPW-ENTADMIN} - 4) Enter administrator
   @{" " LINK GPPW-ENTOWNPW} - 5) Enter own password
        0) Exit program

To execute one of these options, simply type in the relevant number at the 
'Option :-' prompt and press RETURN. Click the buttons above for a
description on what the various options do. "Exit program" is
self-explanatory I think.

                        @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GPPW-LOADPWL "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}1) Load in a PassWord list@{UU}

After asking for confirmation (loading a new password list will delete
all other user information currently in memory) it proceeds to load in
the PassWord List which is stored on disk. Then the user information and
passwords will be available for use.
               
                  @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                  @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GPPW-SAVEPWL "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}2) Save a PassWord list@{UU}

After asking confirmation, this option saves all the current users
information to disk. You can load it in using Option 1, if the program
hasn't loaded it in already.

                  @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                  @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GPPW-CNFPW "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}3) Config PassWord (NEW)@{UU}

To use this function, you need to log in as the administrator or a user.
Use options 4 and 5 on the main menu (described @{"here" LINK GPPW}) to do this.

Once you have logged in, the following menu appears:

   @{" " LINK CNFPW-USERINFO} - 1) Display users information
   @{" " LINK CNFPW-CNFPPW} - 2) Config ProPassWord
   @{" " LINK CNFPW-EDITPW} - 3) Edit administrator/own password
   @{" " LINK CNFPW-ADDUSER} - 4) Add new user
   @{" " LINK CNFPW-EDUSER} - 5) Edit user
   @{" " LINK CNFPW-DELUSER} - 6) Delete user account
   @{" " LINK CNFPW-AEXTIME} - 7) Change auto-expire time
   @{" " LINK CNFPW-VALUSER} - 8) Validate user
        0) Back to main menu

   Click above for a description of the various menu items.

                  @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                  @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CNFPW-USERINFO "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}1) Display users information@{UU}

This simply displays a list of all the currently defined user ID's
and their number. You will be returned to the menu after the list
has ended.
                  
                 @{" " LINK GPPW-CNFPW} - Back to Config PassWord (NEW)
                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CNFPW-CNFPPW "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}2) Config ProPassWord@{UU}

This option lets you alter the various aspects of the main ProPassWord 
program. It is quite a large menu, and here are the options (the
values in the brackets are the default values):

   @{" " LINK CNFPPW-1} - 1) Load ProPassWord config file
   @{" " LINK CNFPPW-2} - 2) Save ProPassWord config file
   @{" " LINK CNFPPW-3} - 3) Delete ProPassWord config file
   @{" " LINK CNFPPW-4} - 4) Where ProPassWord data base is (ETC:PassWD.PPW)
   @{" " LINK CNFPPW-5} - 5) Where ProPassWord access log is (ETC:Finger.log)
   @{" " LINK CNFPPW-6} - 6) Where ProPassWord saves user name  (ENV:UserName)
   @{" " LINK CNFPPW-7} - 7) Name of ProPassWord localhost (localhost)
   @{" " LINK CNFPPW-8} - 8) Where ProPassWord host name saves (ENV:HostName)
   @{" " LINK CNFPPW-9} - 9) Screen blanker delay in seconds (180)
   @{" " LINK CNFPPW-A} - A) ProPassWord Palette
   @{" " LINK CNFPPW-B} - B) Key clear delay in seconds (60)
   @{" " LINK CNFPPW-C} - C) Screen settings (NTSC/PAL/CGFX)
   @{" " LINK CNFPPW-D} - D) Entry Display
        0) Back to main menu

                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

