@NODE CNFPPW-A "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}A) ProPassWord Palette@{UU}

Similar to the Workbench Palette Prefs, this displays a mock-up of
the ProPassWord screen, and a palette designer at the bottom. Select
a colour and alter its RGB values using the  sliders provided. The
changes should be reflected in the mock-up. Hit DEFAULT to return the
colours to their default values. OK accepts the changes, while CANCEL
abandons the changes.

                 @{" " LINK CNFPW-CNFPPW} - Back to Config PassWord (NEW)
                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CNFPPW-B "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}B) Key clear delay in seconds@{UU}

This is a really useful feature. If you begin to enter your username
and password (in PPW) and the telephone rings or the doorbell goes
etc. and you need to leave the desk, the program will automatically
delete any text you entered after the number of seconds set by this
option.   

                 @{" " LINK CNFPW-CNFPPW} - Back to Config PassWord (NEW)
                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CNFPPW-C "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}C) Screen settings (NTSC/PAL/CGFX)@{UU}

Brings up a screen-mode requester. Select from this the mode with
which you would like PPW to run in. After clicking OK a test picture
will be displayed showing what PPW would look like in that mode. To
clear this picture, either wait 15 seconds or press the left mouse
button.

                 @{" " LINK CNFPW-CNFPPW} - Back to Config PassWord (NEW)
                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CNFPPW-D "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}D) Entry Display@{UU}

Allows you to alter the way which PPW displays the username and
password when you are entering it into the program.
 
This option brings up another menu. First of all the program tells
you that the password and username for this menu are PPW and
ProPassWord respectively. That is just to show you what the display
would look like, it is not the actual username/password! 

   @{B}1) Show user name as entered (ProPassWord)@{UB}
   Means that username entry is not hidden in any way whatsoever.
   So any passersby can see your username being entered.

   @{B}2) Show user name as a asterisk (*)@{UB}
   Hides the user name by displaying a single asterisk as you type.
      
   @{B}3) Show user name as asterisk's (***********)@{UB}
   Hides the user name by displaying an asterisk for every character
   you type.

   @{B}4) Show password as entered (PPW)@{UB}
   Means that the password entry is not hidden in any way whatsoever.
   THIS IS NOT RECOMMENDED! Anyone walking by can see your password
   as you type it in! 
 
   @{B}5) Show password as a asterisk (*)@{UB}
   Hides the password by displaying a single asterisk as you type.

   @{B}6) Show password as asterisk's (***)@{UB}
   Hides the password by displaying an asterisk for every character 
   you type.

   @{B}0) Back to config menu@{UB}
   Returns you to the Config ProPassWord menu. 

                 @{" " LINK GPPW-CNFPW} - Back to Config PassWord (NEW)
                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE 

@NODE CNFPW-EDITPW "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}3) Edit administrator/own password@{UU}

This simply lets you change your username and password, depending on
who is logged in, administrator or normal user. 
   
If you are logged in as the administrator, you will be asked for 
confirmation on whether you want to edit your details. Answer Y and
the program asks you for a NEW user name and password, asking you to
confirm entry for each one.

If you are logged in as a normal user (and you have been allowed to
change your own password), you will just be asked for
a new username and password, and then a new ID. The new information
will then be stored.

                 @{" " LINK GPPW-CNFPW} - Back to Config PassWord (NEW)
                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CNFPW-ADDUSER "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}4) Add new user@{UU}

This function allows you to add new user profiles to the PassWord List.
Selecting this option brings up a confirmation prompt asking you if you
want to add new users. Type Y followed by RETURN to continue, otherwise
type N followed by RETURN.

If you enter Y at the prompt, the program will ask you the following
questions:

   @{B}Enter username :-@{UB}
   Enter the new user's username here. It will be displayed on screen.
   
   @{B}Enter  password :-@{UB}
   Enter the new user's password here. It will NOT be shown as you type.

   @{B}Verify  password :-@{UB}
   Re-enter the new user's password here. As before, the password will
   not be shown as you type. 

At this point, if the two password entries were different, you will be
told and put back at the menu. Otherwise, it continues with these prompts:

   @{B}Enter ID :-@{UB}
   Enter the user-id here. This will need to be unique for each user.
   Also, it cannot be made up solely of numbers, there must be some
   alphabetic characters in there somewhere.

   @{B}Enter password reminder :-@{UB}
   Something which may remind the user of their password should they
   forget it. For example, your password might be 'valerie', the name of
   your mother, so the reminder would be 'mother' or something similar.
   
At this point, the program will give you a summary of the details
entered so far. The password will NOT be shown for security reasons.
Now you have some more questions to answer.

   @{B}Enter user security level (-126<>126)?@{UB}
   This is the user's security level, which dictates what actions they 
   can perform on the system.

Now you will be given the option of giving different users different
privileges. Note that if one user does not have a certain privilege, for
example, they cannot change their password, then if they add a new user
themselves, they can not give this privilege to that user.

   @{B}The user can change their own password?@{UB}
   Answer Y if you want the user to be able to alter their password.
   Answering N reserves this right for the administrator only.

   @{B}The user can change their own username?@{UB}
   Answer Y if you want the user to be able to alter their username.
   Answering N reserves this right for the administrator only.
   
   @{B}The user can change their own ID?@{UB}
   Answer Y if you want the user to be able to alter their User ID.
   Answering N reserves this right for the administrator only.
   
   @{B}The user can fix name conflicts?@{UB}
   Answering Y allows the user to fix any name conflicts which may
   occur between them and other users. Answering N means that only
   the administrator can sort out the name conflicts.
 
   @{B}Can add another user to system?@{UB}
   Answer Y if you want to allow the user to add new users to the
   system. Answering N reserves this privilege for the administrator
   only.
    
   @{B}Can delete user from system?@{UB}
   Answer Y if you want to let the user delete others from the system.
   To only allow this privilege to the administrator, answer N. 

   @{B}The user can edit other user status?@{UB}
   Answering Y allows the user to alter other users profiles. Answer N
   to reserve this right for the administrator.
 
   @{B}The user can edit the config?@{UB}
   Allows the user to edit the ProPassWord config if answered with a Y.
   Only allow this to the administrator by answering N instead.
    
At this point, if any of the following are the same, a warning will be
given:
   
   username & password
   username & id
   password & id
     
Now you must confirm the user entry. If all the information is correct,
enter Y, if it is not, enter N to restart, or enter E to exit the 
program and return to the CLI prompt.
           
If you answered Y, and the user ID is valid, the user will be added to
the list. If the user ID is invalid, you will be told and the user will 
NOT be added to the system!

Either way, you will now find yourself back at the menu.

                 @{" " LINK GPPW-CNFPW} - Back to Config PassWord (NEW)
                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CNFPW-EDUSER "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}5) Edit user@{UU}

This option lets you modify the details of any user on the system. If
you are the administrator of the system you are granted this privilege
anyway, but a regular user is only able to do this if they have been
allowed to by the creator of their profile.

After confirming that you want to edit a user's details, the program 
will ask you for the ID of the user. Enter the user ID exactly as it
appears in the 'Display users information' sheet (option 1 on the menu)
and the program will search for the ID. If it finds it, you are asked if
you wish to edit this user. Answer Y to continue, or N to go back to the
menu.

The questions asked in this next section are exactly the same as those
asked when you add a new user, so please read the @{"Add New User" LINK CNFPW-ADDUSER} section
for more information on the questions asked by the program.

The only difference is that if the username/ID have been used before,
the program will inform you and ask you if you want to keep the details.
This constitutes a name conflict, and can only be fixed by the
administrator, or by a user who has been granted the privilege. Answer Y 
to keep the new details, or N to abandon them.

You will now be returned to the menu.

                 @{" " LINK GPPW-CNFPW} - Back to Config PassWord (NEW)
                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CNFPW-DELUSER "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}6) Delete user account@{UU}

If you are a normal user, you are simply asked to give the user ID of
the user to be deleted. Then, for security reasons, this user is placed 
on a LIST of users to be deleted. The users can only be permanently 
deleted by the system administrator (see below)

If you are the system administrator, selecting this option brings up the
following menu:

   1) Display all users who are designed for deletion
   2) Delete ALL users who are designed for deletion
   3) Select a user to be un-designed for deletion
   4) Select a user to be deleted
   0) Back to main menu

Here is a description of the options:

   @{B}1) Display all users who are designed for deletion@{UB}
      Simply shows a list of all the users in the system who have been
      marked for deletion. This does NOT delete any users.

   @{B}2) Delete ALL users who are designed for deletion@{UB}
      This option deletes EVERY USER who is in the list accessed by option
      1. Use this with care unless you know what you are doing, because you
      cannot recover user information without re-entering it!

   @{B}3) Select a user to be un-designed for deletion@{UB}
      This option allows you to enter a user ID and it then it searches for
      that ID in the list from option 1. If it finds it, it removes that ID
      from the list.

   @{B}4) Select a user to be deleted@{UB}
      Use this with care! It asks you for the user ID, and will then
      proceed to delete that user STRAIGHT AWAY if it finds the ID in it's
      list. Remember, you cannot recover lost data, so be careful!

   @{B}0) Back to main menu@{UB}
      Returns you to the menu first shown when starting GPPW. 

                 @{" " LINK GPPW-CNFPW} - Back to Config PassWord (NEW)
                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CNFPW-AEXTIME "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}7) Change auto-expire time@{UU}

This option allows you to change the number of days before a user's
account will expire and be deleted automatically. Entering a value
of 0 will result in the account never expiring, whereas entering a
value between 1 and 9999 will set that figure as the number of days
before the account expires. See the @{"Validate user" LINK CNFPW-VALUSER} section as well.

                 @{" " LINK GPPW-CNFPW} - Back to Config PassWord (NEW)
                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CNFPW-VALUSER "ProPassWord Documentation"
   
@{U}8) Validate user@{UU}

This allows you to validate a user. Enter the user ID you wish to 
validate and if GPPW finds it in its PassWord List you will be asked 
to confirm validation. Answer Y to validate the user, or N to return to the
menu. You need to validate a user if their auto-expire time has been
passed. If you do not, then they will not be able to access the
system without creating a new profile for themselves.

                 @{" " LINK GPPW-CNFPW} - Back to Config PassWord (NEW)
                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GPPW-ENTADMIN "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}4) Enter administrator@{UU}

Selecting this option allows you to log into the system as an
administrator, provided you have the correct username and password of
course. Selecting it from the menu brings up a confirmation prompt
asking you if you want to continue. If you are authorised to use this
function, press Y followed by RETURN. If you are NOT authorised to use
the administrator functions, press N followed by RETURN.

If you answered Y to the confirmation prompt, the program will inform
you that it will keep a record of the attempted access. This means that
if you are NOT authorised to use administration facilities, then the
real administrator will be able to keep checks on who attempts to access
the system. GPPW will again ask you for confirmation. Press Y followed
by RETURN if you are the administrator, or N followed by RETURN to abort
the process.

Pressing Y at the last prompt now brings up the login section. At the
'Enter  username :-' prompt, type in the administrator username EXACTLY
(it is case-sensitive) Don't worry, the characters you type will not be
shown on the CLI window. Note that when you first unarchive the package,
the default username for the administrator is simply 'username' (minus 
the quotes) and the default password is 'password', again, minus the 
quotes. To change the username/password, log on as the administrator
using the defaults), select Config Password from the menu, and then
select option 3, 'Edit administrator password'.

Once you have done this, press RETURN and you will have to do the same,
only this time with the administrator password. Again, the characters you
type will not be shown in the window, and it is case-sensitive.

Assuming that both the username and password were correct, you will now
be granted administrator status, giving you access to everything in the
program. Note that option 4 in the main menu will now have changed to
'Disable administrator' which simply logs out the administrator,
returning everything to normal. Note that if you now try and load a new
password file, or log on as a normal user, administrator status is
automatically dropped.

                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GPPW-ENTOWNPW "ProPassWord Documentation"

@{U}5) Enter own password@{UU}

This is very similar to @{"Enter administrator" LINK GPPW-ENTADMIN} in operation,
with the vital omission being that there is no logging. Why would there need 
to be when only normal users can log in here. The administrator cannot log in
as a normal user, and vice versa.

Simply enter your username and password at the prompts, and press RETURN 
after each entry. The program will then cross-reference your entries with
its database, and if it finds a perfect match, will log you in as that
user, allowing you to access the rest of the system.

                 @{" " LINK GPPW} - Back to GenerateProPassword.
                 @{" " LINK MAIN} - Back to Contents Page.
@ENDNODE

